        <td width="60" height="71" align="left" valign="top" class="cart-blankline"><p>8:30</p></td>
        <td align="left" valign="top" class="cart-blankline"><p><strong>The Story Form Method Why It Works | </strong><em><span class="style21">Keith Belzer, Madison, WI</span><br />
        </em>Keith Belzer is a nationally recognized lecturer and teacher on criminal defense issues, trial techniques and strategies. He is faculty member at the National Criminal Defense College and recently partcipated in OCDLA’s Trial Skills College. He has presented in Israel, Puerto Rico, and The People’s Republic of China.  One of Belzer’s cases, the retrial and exoneration of Evan Zimmerman, a man falsely convicted and sentenced to life in prison for a homicide that he did not commit, was the subject of a feature length documentary: “Facing Life: The Retrial of Evan Zimmerman,” which has been broadcast on the Arts and Entertainment Network and the Biography Channel. Belzer is also a frequent commentator on national, statewide and local legal issues and has appeared on nationally syndicated shows including Good Morning America, The O’Reilly Factor, and Geraldo at Large.</p></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td align="left" valign="top" class="cart-blankline"><p>9:00</p></td>
        <td align="left" valign="top" class="cart-blankline"><p><strong>“If You Build It, They Will Come.” Using Story to Creat Key Moments, Win Difficult Evidentiary Battles, and Vindicate the Client | </strong><em><span class="style21">Cathy Bennett, Committee for Public Counsel Services, Boston, MA</span><br />
        </em>Cathleen Bennett is the Criminal Defense Training Director at the Committee for Public Counsel Services in Boston. She is an adjunct professor in trial advocacy at Boston College Law School, a member of the faculty at the National Criminal Defense College, and has taught trial advocacy across the country. She is the author of the chapter, “Pretrial Conference: Specific Requests” in Trying Sex Offense Cases in Massachusetts and in Trying Murder and Homicide Cases in Massachusetts, as well as other publications. Bennett is the 2007 recipient of the Thurgood Marshall Award presented by the Committee for Public Counsel Services.</p></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td align="left" valign="top" class="cart-blankline"><p>10:00</p></td>
        <td align="left" valign="top" class="cart-blankline"><p>Break</p></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td align="left" valign="top" class="cart-blankline"><p>10:15</p></td>
        <td align="left" valign="top" class="cart-blankline"><p><strong>Direct Examination: Not the Same Old Stuff | </strong><span class="style21"><em>Keith Belzer</em></span></p></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td align="left" valign="top" class="cart-blankline"><p>11:45</p></td>
        <td align="left" valign="top" class="cart-blankline"><p> Lunch (included)</p></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td align="left" valign="top" class="cart-blankline"><p>12:45p</p></td>
        <td align="left" valign="top" class="cart-blankline"><p><strong>Storytelling Through Cross-Examination (lecture &amp; demo) | </strong><span class="style21"><em>Abe Hutt, Denver, CO</em></span><br />
          Abe Hutt successfully defended the writer Hunter S. Thompson on DUI and assault charges, and won dismissal of all charges against a City of Aspen building inspector charged with criminal homicide following the carbon monoxide poisoning of a family of four. He is a frequent CLE lecturer on the subject of trial tactics. He is a member of the Adjunct Faculty at the University of Denver School of Law and a faculty member of the National Criminal Defense College. Hutt has represented clients in the trial courts of every one of Colorado’s 22 judicial districts, the Colorado Supreme Court and Court of Appeals, and the U.S. District Court for Colorado. <br />
        </p></td>
      </tr>
